    <h2>Groups</h2>

    <p>The class is divided into two groups of five or six members each. Each group
      includes a mixture of graduate and undergraduate students. The instructor may choose
      to adjust the membership of any group at any time.</p>

    <p>With the advice and consent of the group members, the group project leaders will
      assign roles to each project member. Different groups may choose to select different
      roles that are filled, but a reasonable set of roles include</p>

    <ul>

      <li>developing one or more specific components</li>
      <li>defining the data exchange formats</li>
      <li>internal documentation (writer or coordinator)</li>

    </ul>

    <p>Each group has two members with assigned roles: a project leader and a team leader.
      The project leader is responsible for the final collection of written submissions. I
      recommend dividing the project into two halves (authoring and viewing) with the team
      leader responsible for this level of work for one of these halves. To balance the
      two halves, I recommend placing responsibility for the stored file format with the
      viewing side. </p>

    <p>Each group should expect to meet as a group several times outside of class. If you
      have problems scheduling a regular time, let me know.</p>

    <p>Group dynamics can be very tricky and, for perhaps your first time, your grade will
      be largely dependent on the performance of your peers. If you believe you have a
      problem within your group, please come see me as soon as possible. I expect to talk
      to at least one person from each group at least once regarding some issue.</p>

    <h2>Tools</h2>

    <p>This course is intended to be largely tool agnostic. One of the first decisions
      that must be made by each group is the choice of platform, language and development
      environment. The course lab in 369a includes sun sparcs with windows cards, so the
      two reasonable platforms are sun/solaris and windows. Let me know as soon as
      possible what platform and development environment you will be using. I will be glad
      to advise any group on this choice. I recommend using either Java or C++ and
      sticking with a language and environment that everyone in the group already knows,
      if possible. This project allows a group to use a mixture of languages, divided by
      program.</p>
